                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">To Zarath:
<br />

<br />
It's all about overall efficiency and RvR. Sure the charmed pet in tipt/vxed is insane dps (you have soe's HURR HURR MOB DPS IS FUN attitude to thank for that), but it's spotty. What about time recovering when shit turns south? What about the times where the group was counting on the pet and the pet broke? 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I'll ignore the personal attacks and vitriol of your post for a moment and focus on this.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Protip: it's vitriolic to backhand someone's post's vitriol.
<br />

<br />
I think the real issue here is DPS penis envy. Always has been, always will be. I'ma toss out what seems to be some kind of weird secret here:
<br />

<br />
Enchanters are not a dps class, but in rare circumstances have the ability to ply their character skill, rather than the numbers on their character sheet, to bring about greatly increased dps. They temporarily shift class roles and take on much greater risk with the reward of increased dps. However, xp per kill goes down, and downtime associated with rezzing and charm breaks further decreases overall efficiency. The major benifit brought by charming is the ability to increase the stakes on both sides such that the group--not the enchanter alone--is able to take on targets it could not have before, IE the tipt final named. Charm is an ability the enchanter brings to the group, but can only be counted as 'omg lookit that chanter dps' in a solo environment, which this nerf didn't change much.
<br />

<br />
If that paragraph didn't make sense it's probably because you're not an enchanter.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
